                        Extra execution time due to monitoring: 4.475211393229622 us = 0.05173125490178093 standard deviations (of the original measurement)

It seems clear that monitoring the memory has very little impact on a cpu intensive operation. (Note: this result was obtained on jdk 6, but when previously tested it on jdk 5, found a modest impact.)

One issue: when the memory state file that is produced by the listener while task runs was examined, it only contained 4,069 entries. Given that interval is being set to interval_test = 1 ms, would have expected ~40 * 1000 ~= 40,000 entries if the monitoring task truly was executed every millisecond. Since writing to the file perhaps takes more than 1 ms, maybe that is part of the explanation. Another factor might be that my PC's clock is so inaccurate that it can only schedule with resolutions down to 10-20 ms.
